# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: navigation-timing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] Navigation Timing is part of the Performance API and provides metrics associated with navigating from one page to another.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] For example, you can determine how much time it takes to load or unload a document, or log the time it took until DOM construction has finished and interaction with the DOM is possible.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] Only the current document is included, so usually there is only one `PerformanceNavigationTiming` object to observe.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] It extends the `PerformanceEntry` interface with the `entryType` of `"navigation"` and also inherits from `PerformanceResourceTiming`, so all of the timestamps from the process of fetching the document are available as well.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] (Timestamp diagram listing timestamps in the order in which they are recorded for the fetching of a document) Figure 1.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] `unloadEventStart`: (if there is a previous document) the timestamp immediately before the current document's `unload` event handler starts.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] `unloadEventEnd`: (if there is a previous document) the timestamp immediately after the current document's `unload` event handler completes.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] `domInteractive`: timestamp when DOM construction is finished and interaction with it from JavaScript is possible.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] `domContentLoadedEventStart`: timestamp immediately before the current document's `DOMContentLoaded` event handler starts.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] `domContentLoadedEventEnd`: timestamp immediately after the current document's `DOMContentLoaded` event handler completes.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] `domComplete`: timestamp when the document and all sub-resources have finished loading.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] `loadEventStart`: timestamp immediately before the current document's `load` event handler starts.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] `loadEventEnd`: timestamp immediately after the current document's `load` event handler completes.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] The `PerformanceNavigationTiming.confidence` property returns a `PerformanceTimingConfidence` object containing information that indicates whether a performance record reflects typical application performance, or is likely affected by external factors.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] For example, if a website has loaded after a browser "cold start" or session restore, its pages may load more slowly as a result.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] In such cases, a `low` confidence `value` would be returned for an associated performance record.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] On the other hand, if the browser determines a returned performance record to be representative of typical application performance, a `high` confidence value is returned.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] This confidence measure is useful for developers when trying to determine whether a performance issue is a legitimate concern, or an outlier being caused by external factors.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] See `PerformanceTimingConfidence` for more information.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] The `PerformanceNavigationTiming` interface provides additional properties such as `redirectCount` returning the number of redirects and `type` indicating the type of navigation.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] The `domContentLoadedEventEnd` and `domContentLoadedEventStart` timestamps can be used to measure how long it takes to process the `DOMContentLoaded` event handler.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] This example uses a `PerformanceObserver`, which notifies the caller about new `navigation` performance entries as they are recorded in the browser's performance timeline.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] The example uses the `buffered` option to access entries that were recorded before the observer was created.
[src:navigation-timing/navigation-timing-api] For more examples, see the property pages in the `PerformanceNavigationTiming` reference documentation.
[src:navigation-timing/performance-timing] The legacy **`Performance.timing`** read-only property returns a `PerformanceTiming` object containing latency-related performance information.
[src:navigation-timing/performance-timing] This property is not available in workers.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] It’s been available across browsers since October 2021.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] The **`PerformanceNavigationTiming`** interface provides methods and properties to store and retrieve metrics regarding the browser's document navigation events.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] For example, this interface can be used to determine how much time it takes to load or unload a document.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] Only the current document is included in the performance timeline, so there is only one `PerformanceNavigationTiming` object in the performance timeline.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] It inherits all of the properties and methods of `PerformanceResourceTiming` and `PerformanceEntry`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] The following diagram shows all of the timestamp properties defined in `PerformanceNavigationTiming`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] Note that text fragments, and any other fragment directives, are stripped from the URL.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] Returns a `DOMHighResTimeStamp` with a value of `0`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] Returns a `timestamp` that is the difference between the `PerformanceNavigationTiming.loadEventEnd` and `PerformanceEntry.startTime` properties.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time between when a document starts prerendering and when it is activated.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A `PerformanceTimingConfidence` object containing information that indicates whether a performance record reflects typical application performance, or is likely affected by external factors.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time at which the connection restart occurred due to `Critical-CH` HTTP response header mismatch.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately before the user agent sets the document's `readyState` to `"complete"`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately after the current document's `DOMContentLoaded` event handler completes.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately before the current document's `DOMContentLoaded` event handler starts.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately before the user agent sets the document's `readyState` to `"interactive"`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately after the current document's `load` event handler completes.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately before the current document's `load` event handler starts.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A `NotRestoredReasons` object providing report data on reasons why the current document was blocked from using the back/forward cache (bfcache) on navigation.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A number representing the number of redirects since the last non-redirect navigation in the current browsing context.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A string representing the navigation type.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately after the current document's `unload` event handler completes.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time immediately before the current document's `unload` event handler starts.
[src:navigation-timing/performancenavigationtiming] Returns a JSON representation of the `PerformanceNavigationTiming` object.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] The **`PerformanceTiming`** interface is a legacy interface kept for backwards compatibility and contains properties that offer performance timing information for various events which occur during the loading and use of the current page.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] You get a `PerformanceTiming` object describing your page using the `window.performance.timing` property.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] These properties each describe the time at which a particular point in the page loading process was reached.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] Some correspond to DOM events; others describe the time at which internal browser operations of interest took place.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] Each time is provided as a number representing the moment, in milliseconds since the UNIX epoch.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] These properties are listed in the order in which they occur during the navigation process.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the prompt for unload terminates on the previous document in the same browsing context.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] If there is no previous document, this value will be the same as `PerformanceTiming.fetchStart`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the `unload` event has been thrown, indicating the time at which the previous document in the window began to unload.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] If there is no previous document, or if the previous document or one of the needed redirects is not of the same origin, the value returned is `0`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the `unload` event handler finishes.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] If there is no previous document, or if the previous document, or one of the needed redirects, is not of the same origin, the value returned is `0`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] If there is no redirect, or if one of the redirects is not of the same origin, the value returned is `0`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the last HTTP redirect is completed, that is when the last byte of the HTTP response has been received.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the browser is ready to fetch the document using an HTTP request.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] This moment is *before* the check to any application cache.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] If a persistent connection is used, or the information is stored in a cache or a local resource, the value will be the same as `PerformanceTiming.fetchStart`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the request to open a connection is sent to the network.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] If the transport layer reports an error and the connection establishment is started again, the last connection establishment start time is given.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] If a persistent connection is used, the value will be the same as `PerformanceTiming.fetchStart`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] If the transport layer reports an error and the connection establishment is started again, the last connection establishment end time is given.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] A connection is considered as opened when all secure connection handshake, or SOCKS authentication, is terminated.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the secure connection handshake starts.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] If no such connection is requested, it returns `0`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the browser sent the request to obtain the actual document, from the server or from a cache.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] If the transport layer fails after the start of the request and the connection is reopened, this property will be set to the time corresponding to the new request.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the browser received the first byte of the response, from the server from a cache, or from a local resource.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the browser received the last byte of the response, or when the connection is closed if this happened first, from the server, the cache, or from a local resource.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the parser started its work, that is when its `Document.readyState` changes to `'loading'` and the corresponding `readystatechange` event is thrown.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the parser finished its work on the main document, that is when its `Document.readyState` changes to `'interactive'` and the corresponding `readystatechange` event is thrown.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] Right before the parser sent the `DOMContentLoaded` event, that is right after all the scripts that need to be executed right after parsing have been executed.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] Right after all the scripts that need to be executed as soon as possible, in order or not, have been executed.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the parser finished its work on the main document, that is when its `Document.readyState` changes to `'complete'` and the corresponding `readystatechange` event is thrown.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the `load` event was sent for the current document.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] If this event has not yet been sent, it returns `0`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] When the `load` event handler terminated, that is when the load event is completed.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] If this event has not yet been sent, or is not yet completed, it returns `0`.
[src:navigation-timing/performancetiming] Returns a JSON object representing this `PerformanceTiming` object.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] In telecommunications, **round-trip delay** (**RTD**) or **round-trip time** (**RTT**) is the amount of time it takes for a signal to be sent *plus* the amount of time it takes for acknowledgement of that signal having been received.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] This time delay includes propagation times for the paths between the two communication endpoints.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] In the context of computer networks, the signal is typically a data packet.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] RTT is commonly used interchangeably with **ping time**, which can be determined with the ping command.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] However, ping time may differ from experienced RTT with other protocols since the payload and priority associated with ICMP messages used by ping may differ from that of other traffic.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] End-to-end delay is the length of time it takes for a signal to travel in one direction and is often approximated as half the RTT.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] RTT is a measure of the amount of time taken for an entire message to be sent to a destination and for a reply to be sent back to the sender.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] The time to send the message to the destination in its entirety is known as the network latency, and thus RTT is twice the latency in the network plus a processing delay at the destination.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] The other sources of delay in a network that make up the network latency are processing delay in transmission, propagation time, transmission time and queueing time.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] Propagation time is dependent on distance.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] Transmission time for a message is proportional to the message size divided by the bandwidth.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] Thus higher bandwidth networks will have lower transmission time, but the propagation time will remain unchanged, and so RTT does fall with increased bandwidth, but the delay increasingly represents propagation time.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] Networks with both high bandwidth and a high RTT (and thus high bandwidth-delay product) can have large amounts of data in transit at any given time.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] Such *long fat networks* require a special protocol design.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] One example is the TCP window scale option.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] where $\alpha$ is constant weighting factor ( $0\leq \alpha <1$ ).
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] Choosing a value for $\alpha$ close to 1 makes the weighted average immune to changes that last a short time (e.g., a single segment that encounters long delay).
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] Choosing a value for $\alpha$ close to 0 makes the weighted average respond to changes in delay very quickly.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] This was improved by the Jacobson/Karels algorithm, which takes standard deviation into account as well.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] Once a new RTT is calculated, it is entered into the equation above to obtain an average RTT for that connection, and the procedure continues for every new calculation.
[src:navigation-timing/round-trip-delay] Accurate round-trip time measurements over Wi-Fi using IEEE 802.11mc are the basis for the Wi-Fi positioning system.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Faster website download speeds have been shown to increase visitor retention and loyalty and user satisfaction, especially for users with slow internet connections and those on mobile devices.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Web performance also leads to less data travelling across the web, which in turn lowers a website's power consumption and environmental impact.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Some aspects which can affect the speed of page load include browser/server cache, image optimization, and encryption (for example SSL), which can affect the time it takes for pages to render.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] The performance of the web page can be improved through techniques such as multi-layered cache, light weight design of presentation layer components and asynchronous communication with server side components.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] In the first decade or so of the web's existence, web performance improvement was focused mainly on optimizing website code and pushing hardware limitations.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] According to the 2002 book *Web Performance Tuning* by Patrick Killelea, some of the early techniques used were to use simple servlets or CGI, increase server memory, and look for packet loss and retransmission.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Although these principles now comprise much of the optimized foundation of internet applications, they differ from current optimization theory in that there was much less of an attempt to improve the browser display speed.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Steve Souders coined the term "web performance optimization" in 2004.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] At that time Souders made several predictions regarding the impact that WPO as an "emerging industry" would bring to the web, such as websites being fast by default, consolidation, web standards for performance, environmental impacts of optimization, and speed as a differentiator.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] One major point that Souders made in 2007 is that at least 80% of the time that it takes to download and view a website is controlled by the front-end structure.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] This lag time can be decreased through awareness of typical browser behavior, as well as of how HTTP works.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Web performance optimization improves user experience (UX) when visiting a website and therefore is highly desired by web designers and web developers.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] They employ several techniques that streamline web optimization tasks to decrease web page load times.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] This process is known as front end optimization (FEO) or content optimization.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] In addition to the techniques listed below, the use of a content delivery network—a group of proxy servers spread across various locations around the globe—is an efficient delivery system that chooses a server for a specific user based on network proximity.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Typically the server with the quickest response time is selected.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Web browsers open separate Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) connections for each Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) request submitted when downloading a web page.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] These requests total the number of page elements required for download.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] However, a browser is limited to opening only a certain number of simultaneous connections to a single host.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] To prevent bottlenecks, the number of individual page elements are reduced using resource consolidation whereby smaller files (such as images) are bundled together into one file.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] This reduces HTTP requests and the number of "round trips" required to load a web page.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Web pages are constructed from code files such JavaScript and Hypertext Markup Language (HTML).
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] As web pages grow in complexity, so do their code files and subsequently their load times.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] File compression can reduce code files by about 40 percent, thereby improving site responsiveness.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Web Caching Optimization reduces server load, bandwidth usage and latency.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] CDNs use dedicated web caching software to store copies of documents passing through their system.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Many website platforms, such as SiteGround, IONOS, Wix, and Hostinger, rely on global CDNs and caching technologies to deliver faster page loads across different geographical regions.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Subsequent requests from the cache may be fulfilled should certain conditions apply.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Web caches are located on either the client side (forward position) or web-server side (reverse position) of a CDN.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Web browsers are also able to store content for re-use through the HTTP cache or web cache.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Requests web browsers make are typically routed to the HTTP cache to validate if a cached response may be used to fulfill a request.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] If such a match is made, the response is fulfilled from the cache.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] This can be helpful for reducing network latency and costs associated with data-transfer.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] The HTTP cache is configured using request and response headers.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Code minification distinguishes discrepancies between codes written by web developers and how network elements interpret code.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Minification removes comments and extra spaces as well as crunch variable names in order to minimize code, decreasing files sizes by as much as 60%.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] In addition to caching and compression, lossy compression techniques (similar to those used with audio files) remove non-essential header information and lower original image quality on many high resolution images.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] These changes, such as pixel complexity or color gradations, are transparent to the end-user and do not noticeably affect perception of the image.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Another technique is the replacement of raster graphics with resolution-independent vector graphics.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Vector substitution is best suited for simple geometric images.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Lazy loading of images and video reduces initial page load time, initial page weight, and system resource usage, all of which have positive impacts on website performance.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] It is used to defer initialization of an object right until the point at which it is needed.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] The browser loads the images in a page or post when they are needed such as when the user scrolls down the page and not all images at once, which is the default behavior, and naturally, takes more time.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Since web browsers use multiple TCP connections for parallel user requests, congestion and browser monopolization of network resources may occur.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Because HTTP/1 requests come with associated overhead, web performance is impacted by limited bandwidth and increased usage.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Instead of a website's hosting server, CDNs are used in tandem with HTTP/2 in order to better serve the end-user with web resources such as images, JavaScript files and Cascading Style Sheet (CSS) files since a CDN's location is usually in closer proximity to the end-user.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] In recent years, several metrics have been introduced that help developers measure various aspects of the performance of their websites.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Modules to measure metrics such as TTFB, FCP, LCP, FP etc are provided with major frontend JavaScript libraries such as React, NuxtJS and Vue.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] Google publishes a library, the core-web-vitals library that allows for easy measurement of these metrics in frontend applications.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] In addition to this, Google also provides the Lighthouse, a Chrome dev-tools component and PageSpeed Insight a site that allows developers to measure and compare the performance of their website with Google's recommended minimums and maximums.
[src:navigation-timing/web-performance] In addition to this, tools such as the Network Monitor by Mozilla Firefox help provide insight into network-level slowdowns that might occur during transmission of data.
